    <!-- FAQ Section -->
    <section class="faq-section">
        <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

        <details class="faq-details">
            <summary>What is a monthly dividend ETF?</summary>
            <p class="faq-answer">A monthly dividend ETF is a fund that distributes income to its shareholders every month, rather than the traditional quarterly schedule. These are popular among retirees and income-focused investors who want regular cash flow. By matching their investment income with their monthly living expenses, investors can simplify their financial planning and budgeting. These funds typically invest in asset classes known for high current income, such as Real Estate Investment Trusts (REITs), preferred stocks, high-yield corporate bonds, and dividend-paying equities, effectively pooling these assets to provide a smooth, consistent payout schedule.</p>
        </details>
        <details class="faq-details">
            <summary>Are high-yield monthly dividend ETFs safe?</summary>
            <p class="faq-answer">Not always. Extremely high yields (e.g., above 8-10%) can sometimes indicate higher risk, capital depreciation, or the use of complex strategies like covered calls which cap upside potential. Always research the underlying assets. A yield that looks too good to be true is often the result of a falling share price rather than an increasing dividend payout. Investors must dig into the fund's prospectus to understand if the yield is supported by fundamental cash flow or if the fund is returning capital to shareholders, which ultimately erodes the principal value of the investment over time.</p>
        </details>
        <details class="faq-details">
            <summary>Do monthly dividend ETFs compound faster?</summary>
            <p class="faq-answer">Yes, slightly. Because dividends are paid out more frequently, reinvesting them monthly allows your capital to compound slightly faster compared to quarterly dividends, assuming the yield remains the same. This phenomenon is due to the mechanics of compound interest; the more frequently interest is added to the principal, the more opportunities there are for interest to earn interest. Over a period of several decades, this slight advantage can result in a meaningfully larger final portfolio balance, making monthly dividend ETFs an attractive option for long-term investors enrolled in Dividend Reinvestment Plans (DRIPs).</p>
        </details>
        <details class="faq-details">
            <summary>What types of assets do monthly dividend ETFs hold?</summary>
            <p class="faq-answer">They commonly hold REITs, preferred stocks, high-yield bonds, dividend-paying equities, or use options strategies (like covered calls) to generate premium income that is distributed monthly. Some of the most popular monthly dividend ETFs use a buy-write strategy, where they hold a basket of stocks and sell call options against them. This generates substantial premium income, but it limits the fund's ability to participate in strong bull markets. Other funds may focus on specific sectors like utilities or midstream energy infrastructure (MLPs), which are legally structured to pass the majority of their cash flow directly to investors.</p>
        </details>
        <details class="faq-details">
            <summary>Are monthly dividends guaranteed?</summary>
            <p class="faq-answer">No, dividends are never fully guaranteed. An ETF's distribution depends on the income generated by its underlying holdings. If those companies cut their dividends, the ETF's payout will likely decrease as well. Economic downturns, rising interest rates, and sector-specific challenges can all pressure the cash flows of the companies within the ETF. It is crucial for investors to look beyond the headline yield and examine the ETF's historical dividend growth rate, the payout ratios of its underlying components, and the overall macroeconomic environment to assess the true sustainability of the monthly income stream.</p>
        </details>
    </section>
